<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-803-702  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 803 702.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  August 27 1990 v4 n31 pS12(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>NIH prescribes Mac IIx for insight into eyesight. (the US NationalInstitutes of Health) (Federal PC supplement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Richardson, Jennifer.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The US National Institutes of Health (NIH) uses an Apple MacintoshIIx to explore ways to improve methods of monitoring and chartingthe growth of cataracts.andP;  Sophisticated ophthalmological camerasare connected to the Macintosh and other microcomputers to renderdigitized images of the development of cataracts in near realtime.andP;  NIH researchers hope that use of the computerized imageswill help introduce progressive drug treatments to cataractsufferers in place of surgery as well as to improve methods ofdetecting and identifying different types of cataracts.andP;  Onetechnique being developed uses a special video camera called aZeiss Scheimpflug that is able to render a digitized image of acataract for viewing and analysis in only 125 microseconds,avoiding the cumbersome delays of previous methods.andP;  The agencychose to use a Macintosh because of its imaging capabilities andits compatibility with the NIH's Image public-domain softwarepackage.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Product:   Apple Macintosh IIX (Microcomputer) (medical use).andO;Topic:     Government AgencyNational GovernmentEyeMedical ResearchMedical DiagnosisImaging TechnologyNew TechniqueUnited States. National Institutes of Health.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>